Species distribution maps for West Gippsland 2021-2022

DG Nicholls

01 November 2022 at 13:23

Introduction

The Bushlands of Western Port between Nyora and Granville were surveyed with camera trapping byu the Southern Brown Bandicoot Regional Recvodery Group between 2012 to April 2022. The report, Report to Investor Bass Coast Camera Trapping included a map showing the distribution of the Southern Brown Bandicoot but no other species. This paper address that short coming with maps of the species where there are sufficient observations.

Interactive maps are created for species of interest. The observations of mammals species are mapped with a selection of the bird and two reptiles. The base map can be selected (using the layers icon on the left.).

Methods

Data sets

We use the Stations.new1 CTtable. This has the attributes of the Stations plus six extra appended attributes, namely the Mga coordinates, Latitude-Longitude (GDA94 decimal degrees), and two fields that measure the difference between the manually entered coordinates and the the coordinates derived programatically from the GIS file.

The camtrapR record table is here as the Species R data frame.

Work flow

For the pdf maps

  • access R_CENTRAL_DATA and _UTILITIES
  • get Stations.new1
    • subset for the West Gippsland stations (excluding the pre 2020 March records )
    • identify the remaining records where there are no coordinates
  • merge Species and the selected West Gippsland Stations to add location coordinates to the Species table
  • identify the list of species, species_available, some 70 species
  • make a list of a selection; common mammals, interesting species, a few birds, reptiles; species_selected
  • prepare a base map with sf package and ggplot, bmap. Not used instead use sp
  • with sp change locality, llpg and PVres into R objects
  • with a for loop, cycle through the species_selected
  • using ggplot to produce a PDF file the species records on the base map.

For the interactive maps (used here)

  • set eval = FALSE for PDF maps
  • remove existing R object
  • set shapefilename
  • call camtrapR::detectionMaps to create shapefile
  • with mapview display shalefile

Species frequency

Markers or quality control pointers (e.g. first, start) and inadequately identified records are removed. N.B. This repeats script in 4_Summary_Tables_All. We have to decide if these scripts are run in order as a set, or each script will run independently. Here, I am assuming the script will run independently.

Base Map with sf

Use the modern package sf.

Species maps

The maps include locality (as defined by DELWP), conservation reserves and trapping stations (black dot) and species present (red square).
